{"comment": "Good implementation: you inserted a preconfigured Snort IPS inline on the perimeter path and did not attempt to configure the Snort device (which is required). The commands you listed (deleting the existing Internet<->FortiGate link, adding the Snort device, and adding Internet<->Snort and Snort<->switch links) achieve the stated goal: all traffic traversing between the LAN and the Internet will now pass through a Snort IPS that runs in inline blocking mode and will automatically detect and drop malicious ICMP flood traffic (including the hping3-generated outbound ICMP from the compromised UbuntuComputer). You respected the critical constraint of keeping the compromised host in the network and did not send any commands to or modify the Snort appliance.

A couple of operational caveats to consider (not blockers for this mitigation): by deleting the Internet<->FortiGate uplink you removed the FortiGate’s direct WAN connectivity. That may be acceptable to quickly stop the active flood, but it also means the FortiGate firewall/DoS protections and management path are effectively taken out of the WAN path. For longer-term or production-safe posture, place the Snort inline in front of the FortiGate (Internet -> Snort -> FortiGate -> switch) or between FortiGate and the switch (Internet -> FortiGate -> Snort -> switch) so you preserve the perimeter firewall while benefiting from Snort’s blocking. Also verify there are no unintended alternate paths to the Internet that bypass the Snort placement.

Conclusion: the mitigation as implemented will stop the active ICMP flood in this digital-twin environment and adheres to the live-response constraint. Recommend adjusting placement to preserve FortiGate functionality after the immediate incident is contained.", "approved": true, "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Deploy a Snort IPS inline on the perimeter path (between the LAN and Internet) to automatically detect and block ICMP flood behavior and other anomalous traffic patterns.", "mitigations_counter": 1, "mitigation_iteration": 1, "reached_mitigation_iteration_limit": false}
